WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.851
MetaObjects generates your code.

2
00:00:02.851 --> 00:00:04.541
But it doesn't have to.

3
00:00:04.541 --> 00:00:11.153
The same model can drive your app live, at runtime — and that's a different kind of power.

4
00:00:11.153 --> 00:00:12.989
This is runtime metadata.

5
00:00:14.389 --> 00:00:20.647
One generic function built this grid — the columns, the headers, the cell types — straight from the live model.

6
00:00:20.647 --> 00:00:21.718
No code generation.

7
00:00:21.718 --> 00:00:25.214
And the same function does it for any object you've described.

8
00:00:25.214 --> 00:00:26.116
Let me show you.

9
00:00:27.516 --> 00:00:29.527
There are two ways to use one model.

10
00:00:29.527 --> 00:00:33.327
Generate code from it — a photograph, perfect until something moves.

11
00:00:33.327 --> 00:00:37.406
Or load the model at runtime and drive behavior directly — the live feed.

12
00:00:37.406 --> 00:00:38.524
Most teams use both.

13
00:00:39.924 --> 00:00:41.536
So here's the model itself.

14
00:00:41.536 --> 00:00:48.222
Look closely — the validators live right on the fields, and the grid layout sits beside them, all just metadata.

15
00:00:48.222 --> 00:00:54.133
This one file is what the runtime reads; everything you're about to see is driven straight from it.

16
00:00:55.533 --> 00:00:56.902
Here's the live one.

17
00:00:56.902 --> 00:01:03.130
Build grid loads your model and walks it — fields, views, types — and returns your columns.

18
00:01:03.130 --> 00:01:06.895
Notice what's not here: no object name, no field names.

19
00:01:06.895 --> 00:01:12.028
The same call works for Task, for Project, and for anything else you model.

20
00:01:13.428 --> 00:01:16.460
That's the whole thing — a few generic lines.

21
00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:20.706
The rows carry their own model, so it asks each one what it is.

22
00:01:20.706 --> 00:01:25.558
Task, Project, Invoice — one function renders them all, with no codegen.

23
00:01:26.958 --> 00:01:28.500
And it's not just grids.

24
00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:31.071
Validation runs from the live model too.

25
00:01:31.071 --> 00:01:38.591
No generated validator — the required, length, and pattern rules come straight from the metadata, checked at runtime.

26
00:01:39.991 --> 00:01:53.761
Load the model, and it drives a whole lot: dynamic CRUD, validation, relationships, server-driven grids and forms, your entities as LLM tools, prompt rendering and tolerant extraction — none of it regenerated.

27
00:01:55.161 --> 00:01:58.546
So when do you generate, and when do you drive it live?

28
00:01:58.546 --> 00:02:02.853
Generate for build-time artifacts — typed, committed, dependency-free.

29
00:02:02.853 --> 00:02:11.468
Drive it live when codegen can't reach: a shipped app you can't redeploy, an agent that connects tomorrow, behavior that changes on the fly.

30
00:02:11.468 --> 00:02:13.315
A photograph can't reach them.

31
00:02:13.315 --> 00:02:14.361
A live model can.

32
00:02:15.761 --> 00:02:16.908
That's the idea.

33
00:02:16.908 --> 00:02:22.141
Codegen is a photograph of your model; runtime metadata is the live feed.

34
00:02:22.141 --> 00:02:26.514
Same model — generate the code, or drive it live, often both.

35
00:02:26.514 --> 00:02:29.310
Change the model, and behavior follows.

36
00:02:29.310 --> 00:02:32.393
Nothing to regenerate, nothing to redeploy.

37
00:02:33.793 --> 00:02:35.894
Drive your app from the model.

38
00:02:35.894 --> 00:02:38.556
Build grid ships in runtime-web today.

39
00:02:38.556 --> 00:02:43.390
This is part of the MetaObjects series — more at metaobjects dot dev.

40
00:02:43.390 --> 00:02:44.791
Thanks for watching.

